\section{Experimental Design: Buying Votes in the Lab}

% formal model
Formal models can usually help experimentalists to determine which theoretical settings and equilibria are most relevant to a particular causal hypothesis (\cite{McDermott2002}, \cite{Aldrich2011} and \cite[174]{Barberis2013}). Thus, in \autoref{formal:model} we developed a vote-buying game within the Downsian ``spatial'' paradigms \parencite{Downs:1957vg,Enelow:1990aa}. The idea was to test the normative accuracy of the game-theory model in an experimental context (\cite{Lupia:1998ub}, \cite[559]{Bassi2011}, \cite{Dickson2011}, \cite[361]{Tyszler2016}, \cite[1]{Vieider2019}).

%The model tried to account for several alternative causal explanations of vote buying. While there are a number of important issues that have been studied, the model paid attention to three of what we consider are the main ones. 



% role
Building on the formal model, we designed a lab economic experiment. As \autoref{experimental:design:fig} shows, at the beginning of every game, participants received a role at random. Following \textcite{Dickson2011}, roles were presented using neutral terminology to maximize experimental control. The design incorporated the following roles: \emph{party A}, \emph{party B}, or \emph{voter}. Every game was played among three players (one \emph{party A}, one \emph{party B}, and one \emph{voter}).

\begin{figure}[h]
\includegraphics[scale=.9, center]{Experimental_Flow_Figure.pdf}
\caption{{\bf Experimental Flow and Timing of the Voting Game.\label{experimental:design:fig}}}
\caption*{{\bf Note}: At the beginning of each experimental session, all participants were required to successfully complete two practice rounds. A total of \Sexpr{as.numeric(length(unique(v.buying.dat$participant.code)))} subjects were recruited. Each subject played the game three times, for a total sample size of \Sexpr{as.numeric(nrow(dat.v.b))}. For every new game, a whole new randomization process took place. Formally, we follow an in-between-subjects design, where different groups of individuals are randomly assigned to various experimental or control conditions.}\centering
\end{figure}

 
% ideology 1
Voters were assigned an ``ideological'' position at random. That is, voters received at random a certain number of experimental points depending on whether party A or B won the election. For example, if party A won the election, the voter would receive 2,400 points, whereas if party B won the election, the voter would receive 200 points. Hence, the voter in this example should feel ``ideologically'' closer to party A. Critically, this piece of information was not presented to participants as ``ideology,'' but as the points either electoral outcome would give. In turn, parties also received an ``ideological'' position that made them ``closer'' or ``farther way'' from the voter.  

% ideology 2
Substantively, this design accomplishes two goals. First, it models party-voter spatial distances, as considered by traditional voting theories \parencite{Downs:1957vg, Enelow:1990aa}. The basic premise of this paradigm is that the set of candidates that are ideologically closer to a voter produce more utility in the form of fiscal policies, either in terms of redistributive or free-market oriented policies (\cite{Acemoglu:1996rm,Boix:2003db}, but importantly, see \cite{Haggard:2016vr}). Second, it enables us to incorporate both the clientelist targeting and the core/swing voter debates.\footnote{Due to space concerns, we do not expand on this debate from a prospect theory standpoint. Additionally, we only consider these two ideal types of voters. There are other types that we do not discuss in this paper for simplicity. For instance, \textcite[7]{Zarazaga2015a} introduces another category---``conditional supporters''---who ``will vote for the party machine only as long as unexpected events do not persuade them to do otherwise.'' In addition to that, we acknowledge that (single-issue) spatial distances might roughly sort core and swing voters in an ideological continuum. Hence, we believe that core voters should be closer to parties while swing voters should be farther away.} We believe it is relevant to account for these issues because the vote-buying literature seems to be quite divided. In fact, \textcite[14]{Carlin2015} state that ``our knowledge of who parties target remains incomplete.'' On the one hand, \textcite{Cox1986a} and \textcite[7]{Zarazaga2015a} explain that since constituencies are well known to clientelist parties, they allocate resources to core voters. On the other hand, \textcite{Lindbeck1987,Dixit1996,Dahlberg2002,Stokes2005} argue that since allocating resources to individuals who \emph{ex ante} vote for the party is a waste, parties target swing voters. By devising a formal model and an experimental design that considers single-issue ideological positions for both parties and voters, it was then possible to allow parties to target their own/rival supporters. 


% endowments
Next, parties received different ``endowments'' at random as well. Note that both parties receive the same endowment. Since our experimental design is an in-between-subjects design, we should be able to observe and exploit the statistical differences (if any) across ``parties'' with different endowments. Participants acting the ``party'' role accumulated or lost wealth depending on whether they are elected or not elected. Every time they bought votes at some amount, that amount was discounted from their wealth. 

The substantive idea was to reflect the fact that some parties are wealthier than others, a factor that might increase the probability of vote buying  \parencite{Juan-Pablo-Luna:2014wp}. Importantly, it is not clear whether having more resources leads to more clientelism. On the one hand, \textcite{Szwarcberg2013} explains that having economic and material resources available does not necessarily cause more vote buying. Similarly, \textcite[147]{Hagene2015} finds that political clientelism is ``perfectly possible without controlling public funds.'' On the other hand, \textcite{Bahamonde2018} explains that parties with larger budgets will engage in more expensive forms of clientelism, even buying votes from the wealthy. Thus, the formal model and the experiment might shed light on these issues.

Finally, participants acting the ``voter'' role accumulated or lost wealth depending on whether their party was elected or not elected (as per traditional spatial voting theories) and on whether they decided to sell or not sell their vote. For simplicity, voters received zero initial endowments. It is important to note that following our formal model and \textcite[371]{Tyszler2016}, both ideology and party endowments were common knowledge among participants. 



% vote share
Moving forward, both parties received at random an initial vote share, that is, a \emph{certain} number of (fictional) voters that were going to cast their votes for each party. Overall, this experimental condition mimics the degree to which an election is contested. In particular, this portion of the design accomplishes two goals. First, it puts parties in different electoral contestation environments. In other words, it introduces the element of risk (of losing the election) in the game. Since voters win or lose points when their parties win or lose elections, this risk is also relevant for players acting the ``voter'' role. Second, it gives (or not) voters a certain amount of electoral leverage. Since \textcite{Downs:1957vg}, traditional spatial theories of voting have considered that pivotal voters have more weight in an election, and hence, they might have incentive to sell their vote at higher prices. It is key in our experimental design that all these pieces of information are public.

% pivotal
%Third, it allows to consider whether pivotal voters where targeted by clientelist parties more often than non-pivotal voters. Since \textcite{Downs:1957vg}, traditional spatial theories of voting have considered pivotal voters as more decisive. %Hence, in the model we accounted for such electoral scenarios. All in all, the formal model tries to incorporate these factors that might explain different vote-buying dynamics. 



During the second stage, parties decide whether to buy votes and make an offer to the voter. Experimental subjects acting the ``party'' role that want to buy votes enter a number of points, which ranged from zero to the maximum assigned budget in that round.\footnote{Participants acting the ``party'' role are told that offering a zero amount means that they do not want to buy votes at that time.} The design allows for simultaneous offers (i.e., offers from both parties), one offer, or zero offers. In the third stage, voters evaluate offers (if any). If the party(s) decided that it (they) did not want to make an offer at that time, the voter is told that the party(s) did not make an offer. Voters are told that accepting the offer necessarily implies voting for that party.\footnote{For simplicity, we did not include the possibility of defecting. We encourage future designs to include this feature.} 




% administrative
Finally, the experiment was conducted in Chile by the \emph{Centre for Experimental Social Sciences (CESS)} administered by the \emph{University of Santiago} and \emph{Oxford University, Nuffield College} between \Sexpr{min(format(as.Date(dat$participant.time_started), format="%B %d %Y"))} and \Sexpr{max(format(as.Date(dat$participant.time_started), format="%B %d %Y"))}. It was programmed in \texttt{O-tree}, the online version of \texttt{Z-tree} \parencite{Fischbacher2007}. Following \textcite{Harrison2006} and others, our experimental design minimizes hypothetical bias and ``cheap talk'' by compensating subjects with real money according to their decisions \parencite{Morton:2010ly,Dickson2011}. At the beginning of each experimental session all participants were required to successfully complete two practice rounds.\footnote{To make sure participants understood the dynamics of the game, they were shown two examples of the voting game. Participants were required to enter the correct number of points each hypothetical participant would have received in each example. Importantly, all actual participants had to enter the exact number of points to continue playing the game.} Those data were not used in the statistical analyses. In addition, subjects received a show-up payment of \$2,000 CLP ($\approx$ \texteuro2.1). Payoffs depended on the quality of individual decisions.\footnote{\textcite[95]{Levy1997} notes that in poorer societies (like the Chilean society), conducting research with relatively smaller monetary incentives is still meaningful. However, see \textcite{Morton:2010ly,Bassi2011}.} \autoref{payoffs:plot:fig} shows the distribution of payoffs expressed in actual currency, by role. \autoref{summary:stats:t} shows summary statistics broken down by pre-treatment observables. These covariates were captured by a battery of socio-demographic questions delivered at the end of the study.\footnote{The table also details the same information conveyed in \autoref{payoffs:plot:fig}.} A total of \Sexpr{as.numeric(length(unique(v.buying.dat$participant.code)))} subjects were recruited. Each subject played the game three times. The total sample size is \Sexpr{as.numeric(nrow(dat.v.b))}. For every new game, a whole new randomization process took place.\footnote{That is, participants received a role, an ``ideology,'' a party endowment and a contestability structure.} Formally, we follow an in-between-subjects design, where different groups of individuals are randomly assigned to various experimental or control conditions \parencite{McDermott2002,Tyszler2016,Hwang2021}.


