% experimental points
Finally, all transactions were performed exchanging experimental ``points.'' We endeavored to employ neutral terminology to maximize experimental control \parencite{Dickson2011}. Thus, throughout all three games, participants bought and sold votes (if any) and accumulated and lost wealth expressed purely in experimental points. Every experimental point was equivalent to \$\Sexpr{as.numeric(unique(dat$session.config.real_world_currency_per_point))} CLP ($\approx$ \texteuro0.00045). Participants learned about the conversion when reading the initial instructions. Final payoffs were converted to actual currency at the end of the study.



\section{Statistical Analyses: Risk and Vote Buying}


% internal validity
Since the focus of this paper is on vote-buying, we discarded the voter data and analyzed all observations $i$ acting any of the party roles (\emph{party A} and \emph{party B}). In practice, this leaves the data formatted in party-voter dyads. Moving forward, in this paper, we concentrate on one main dependent variable, namely, the amount of the vote-buying offers made by parties (if any). The distribution of such this variable is shown in \autoref{dep:var:plot:fig}. 

